\begin{thm}[Gelfand-Naimark]
	Every $C^\ast$-algebra has a faithful representation.
\end{thm}
\begin{proof}
	Let $A$ be a $C^\ast$-algebra. Suppose we have a collection $\{\phi_i ~|~i\in I\}$ of 
	representations of $A$ on Hilbert spaces $\{\H_i ~|~ i\in I\}$.
	For $a$ in $A$, we have $\|\phi_i(a)\|\leq \|a\|$ (as each $\phi_i$ is a $\ast$-homomorphism),
	so we have a bounded operator $\oplus\phi_i(a)$ on $\oplus \H_i$ by section \ref{hscons}. By the
	properties of $\oplus\phi_i(a)$ stated therein, the map 
	\[
		\phi:A\to \B(\oplus\H_i):a\mapsto\oplus\phi_i(a)
	\]
	is a $\ast$-homomorphism, and so is a representation of $A$ on $\oplus\H_i$. Call $\phi$ the 
	\emph{direct sum representation} of $A$ on $\oplus\H_i$, denoted $\oplus\phi_i$.
	
	With $\S_0$ any collection of states on $A$ containing $\P{A}$, let $\phi$ be the direct sum of
	the collection $\{\pi_\rho ~|~ \rho\in\S_0\}$ of representations as constructed by the GNS
	construction. We show that $\phi$ is a faithful representation.
	
	Now for any $a\not=0$ in $A$, there is a pure state on $A$ such that $\rho(a)\not=0$. By the GNS
	construction, $\rho(a)= \langle \pi_\rho (a) x_\rho, x_\rho \rangle$, so $\pi_\rho\not=0$.
	
\end{proof}




